# Testing

Toupee uses two layers of testing: unit tests in source modules and integration tests driven by `.test` files.

## Running tests

```bash
# Run everything (unit tests + integration tests)
zig build test

# Run fuzz tests
zig build fuzz

# Run benchmarks (ReleaseFast)
zig build bench
```

## Unit tests

Unit tests live at the bottom of each source file using Zig's built-in `test` blocks. They cover internal functions and edge cases that are hard to express in the integration test format.

Current unit test locations:
- `Parser.zig` -- tag parsing, attribute extraction, element classification
- `Renderer.zig` -- node rendering, value resolution, error detail population
- `Node.zig` -- struct construction and field access
- `Value.zig` -- tagged union operations, dot-path resolution, map/list access
- `transform.zig` -- individual transform implementations
- `root.zig` -- Engine lifecycle, caching, RenderResult
- `indent.zig` -- indentation tracking
- `format.zig` -- HTML pretty-printing

## Integration test format

Integration tests use `.test` files in the `test/` directory. Each file contains multiple test cases separated by `<!-- test: name -->` markers.

### Basic structure

```html
<!-- test: descriptive name -->
<!-- in -->
template source here
<!-- context -->
{"data": {"key": "value"}}
<!-- out -->
expected output here
```

### Sections

- `<!-- test: name -->` -- starts a new test case (required)
- `<!-- in -->` -- template source (required)
- `<!-- context -->` -- JSON data; `data` for variables, `templates` for includes (optional)
- `<!-- out -->` -- expected rendered output (optional; if absent, error is expected)
- `<!-- error -->` -- expected error type name (optional)

### Context JSON format

```json
{
  "data": {
    "title": "Hello",
    "items": ["a", "b", "c"],
    "user": {"name": "Alice", "active": true}
  },
  "templates": {
    "header.html": "<header>Header</header>",
    "card.html": "<div class=\"card\"><t-slot /></div>"
  }
}
```

- `data` -- key-value pairs accessible as template variables
- `templates` -- named templates accessible via `t-include` and `t-extend`

### Error assertions

For tests that verify error reporting, use these directives:

```html
<!-- test: undefined variable error detail -->
<!-- in -->
<t-var name="missing" />
<!-- context -->
{"data": {}}
<!-- error -->
UndefinedVariable
<!-- error-line: 1 -->
<!-- error-column: 1 -->
<!-- error-kind: undefined_variable -->
<!-- error-message: missing -->
```

Available error directives:
- `<!-- error-line: N -->` -- expected line number (1-based)
- `<!-- error-column: N -->` -- expected column number (1-based)
- `<!-- error-kind: name -->` -- expected `ErrorDetail.Kind` enum tag (snake_case)
- `<!-- error-message: text -->` -- text that must appear in the error message

All four are optional and can be used in any combination. They only apply when the test expects an error.

### Tips

- Trailing whitespace is trimmed from expected output lines
- Empty lines in expected output are preserved
- Context is optional; omitting it means empty data
- Use `"templates"` in context JSON to provide includes

## Writing new tests

1. Choose the most appropriate `.test` file for the feature being tested
2. Add a test case with a descriptive name
3. Keep templates minimal -- test one thing per case
4. For error tests, include error detail assertions when possible
5. Run `zig build test` to verify

### Naming conventions

Test names should be lowercase, descriptive, and grouped by feature:

```html
<!-- test: var with dotted path -->
<!-- test: var with missing default -->
<!-- test: var with chained transforms -->
```

### Edge case testing

Edge cases go in `test/edge.test`. This file covers:
- Empty and whitespace-only templates
- Unicode and emoji in values
- Very long values
- Deeply nested structures
- Adjacent template elements with no whitespace

## Fuzz testing

`src/fuzz.zig` contains two fuzz targets:

1. **Parser fuzz** -- sends random bytes to `Parser.parse()`, verifying it never crashes
2. **Renderer fuzz** -- parses then renders random input with empty context

Fuzz targets use `std.testing.fuzz` with seed corpora of representative template strings. Run with `zig build fuzz`.

## Benchmarks

`src/bench.zig` measures four operations on a realistic template:

| Benchmark | What it measures |
|-----------|------------------|
| Parse | `Parser.parse()` on a template with loops and conditionals |
| Render | `Renderer.render()` with 10 data items |
| Cached render | `Engine.renderTemplate()` using pre-cached IR |
| Full pipeline | `Engine.render()` including parse + render |

Run with `zig build bench` (compiles with ReleaseFast).

## Test file list

| File | Coverage |
|------|----------|
| `var.test` | `t-var`: escaping, defaults, transforms, dotted paths |
| `raw.test` | `t-raw`: unescaped output, transforms |
| `transform.test` | All 20 built-in transforms |
| `conditional.test` | `t-if`, `t-elif`, `t-else`: equality, existence, nesting |
| `loop.test` | `t-for`: lists, sort, limit/offset, metadata |
| `slot.test` | `t-slot`, `t-define`: named slots, defaults |
| `extend.test` | `t-extend`: inheritance chains, slot overrides |
| `include.test` | `t-include`: attributes, nested includes |
| `let.test` | `t-let`: variable capture, transforms |
| `comment.test` | `t-comment`: stripped from output |
| `bind.test` | `t-var:`, `t-attr:` attribute bindings |
| `nesting.test` | Complex nested combinations |
| `error.test` | Error conditions with detail assertions |
| `integration.test` | Multi-feature scenarios |
| `edge.test` | Boundary conditions and unusual inputs |
